			>
			</li>
			<li>
				<DarkModeToggle />
			</li>
		</ul>
	</nav>
	<main
		class="relative mx-auto flex max-w-2xl flex-col gap-6 p-6 pt-0 sm:grid sm:grid-cols-2"
	>
		<div
			class="fixed -inset-6 top-16 z-10 h-20 bg-gradient-to-b from-gray-200 from-10% to-transparent to-80% dark:from-gray-800"
		>
		</div>
		<section id="top" class="col-span-2 space-y-4">
			<SectionTitle title="ðŸ‘‹ Hey Tailwind team!" href="#top" />
			<div
				class="font-extended absolute left-0 right-0 top-12 text-center text-[.5rem] font-bold text-gray-950/5 dark:text-white/5"
			>
				obligatory waving hand emoji on design portfolio
			</div>
			<!-- <p>
				I'm incredibly excited to tell you more about myself and why
				I'll be your next Design Engineer!
			</p> -->
			<div class="card col-span-2 mb-0 flex gap-4 max-sm:flex-col">
				<div class="relative h-fit w-fit shrink-0">
					<Image
						src={mePfp}
						alt="Alex Mueller standing in front of a UConn sign."
						class="aspect-square size-24 rounded-xl object-cover"
						loading="eager"
					/>

					<div
						class="absolute -bottom-1 -right-1 rounded-full border-2 border-dotted border-sky-500 bg-sky-400 p-1 text-xl text-white outline outline-2 outline-gray-100 dark:border-sky-300 dark:outline-gray-700"
					>
						<Icon name="mdi:tailwind" />
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="flex flex-col justify-center">
					<h1
						class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 sm:text-4xl dark:text-white"
					>
						Alex Mueller
					</h1>
					<p class="text-md max-w-prose sm:text-2xl">
						2024 Tailwind Labs Design Engineer
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<p>
				My name is Alex Mueller and I'm excited for the opportunity to
				apply for this role! As soon as I saw the job posting, I knew I
				had to get to work on an application.
			</p>
		</section>
		<section id="about" class="col-span-2 space-y-4">
			<SectionTitle
				href="#about"
				title="About Me"
				icon="mingcute:emoji-line"
				colors="border-yellow-400 bg-yellow-200 text-yellow-800 dark:bg-yellow-600 dark:text-white dark:border-yellow-500"
			/>
			<p>
				Right now, I'm a UX Developer for
				<Link href="https://corcentric.com">Corcentric,</Link> doing both
				front end development and interface design. I've spent the last year
				creating a design system for a brand new platform of products we're
				developing. As 1 of only 3 designers on the team, I have sole responsibility
				and ownership over the design system, which has been tricky but rewarding.
			</p>
			<p>
				For one of our current products, I created a mini library of CSS
				utility classes in SASS, mostly inspired by Tailwind. Our suite
				of developers primarily focus on back end work, so creating this
				library has been helpful in allowing them to style components
				without needing to dive into our already several thousand line
				long CSS files and add a one off rule.
			</p>
			<p>
				Prior to Corcentric, I graduated from the University of
				Connecticut in 2022 with a Bachelor of Arts in Digital Media and
				Design. During my time there, I worked as a UX Engineer at
				<Link href="https://greenhousestudios.uconn.edu/">
					Greenhouse Studios,</Link
				> designing and developing
				<Link href="https://sourceryapp.org/">Sourcery</Link> and
				<Link
					href="https://greenhousestudios.uconn.edu/projects/charles-vr"
				>
					CharlesV|R.
				</Link>
				Also while in school, I held 3 summer internships with <Link
					href="https://www.travelers.com/">Travelers</Link
				>working on their design system and several internal dashboards.
			</p>
			<!-- <SectionTitle
				href="#love"
				title="I love design."
				icon="mingcute:heart-line"
				colors="border-red-400 bg-red-200 text-red-800 dark:bg-red-500 dark:text-white dark:border-red-400"
			/> -->
			<h3 class="font-extended font-semibold">
				Simply put, I love design.
			</h3>
			<p>I truly think this is one of my biggest strengths, if not #1.</p>
			<p>
				I love the work that I do, which makes it so easy to do it well.
				Learning how to improve isn't just something I do to advance my
				career, it's something I'm naturally compelled to do.
			</p>
			<p>
				I started my journey into design when I was a teen. I always had
				an interest in coding as that's what my dad did for a job, but I
				had never really coded myself. Since I use the internet so
				often, I wanted to learn how to make websites.
			</p>
			<p>
				I started by tinkering with some CSS using the browser extension
				Stylebot (which I still use!) and slowly learned just by messing
				around with existing websites.
			</p>
			<h3 class="font-extended font-semibold">I'm quick to adapt.</h3>
			<p>
				Ever since I was a child, I've been a fast learner. Picking up
				new skills and concepts has always come naturally to me, which
				has been a huge asset throughout my life. I think in every
				previous role there's been a new language or framework to learn,
				and I've consistently been able to start making contributions
				quicker than expected.
			</p>
			<div class="space-y-1">
				<p>Currently, I have experience working with:</p>
				<ul class="list-inside list-disc">
					<li>Vanilla HTML, CSS, JS</li>
					<li>Bootstrap, TailwindCSS</li>
					<li>Angular, Vue, Svelte, Astro</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<p>
				This site uses Astro with the Tailwind integration. My <Link
					href="https://muellr.xyz">portfolio</Link
				> uses Svelte with Tailwind as well. I enjoy using Astro for its
				high performance, and Svelte for its developer experience.
			</p>
			<p>
				While working with Angular or Vue was manageable, in terms of JS
				frameworks, I've actively enjoyed working with Svelte. Astro is
				great for a static site like this, as it gives you the strengths
				of a framework, like components, layouts, and modules, without a
				lot of the performance overhead.
			</p>
			<p>
				I know Tailwind Labs uses a lot of React, so while I've
				unfortunately never used React in a project before, I of course
				know of React, and anticipate I would be able to pick it up
				quite quickly, especially given my experience using other JS
				frameworks.
			</p>
		</section>
		<div id="work" class="col-span-2 space-y-2">
			<SectionTitle
				href="#work"
				title="My Work"
				icon="mingcute:components-line"
				colors="border-violet-400 bg-violet-200 text-violet-800 dark:bg-violet-500 dark:text-white dark:border-violet-400"
			/>
			<p>
				Throughout my career, I've worked on many projects, some simply
				code, some simply designs, and some a combo of both. I'd
				recommend looking at my <Link href="https://muellr.xyz"
					>portfolio,</Link
				> which contains more in depth looks at some of my work (though slightly
				out of date), but here are a few highlights.
			</p>
			<div class="card">
				<Image
					src={moonsound}
					alt="An artist page for Lil Uzi Vert, featuring a glassmorphic interface, consisting of a hero image of the artist, with buttons below reading Shuffle and Radio. Below, the artist's latest released album or song, followed by a list of their most popular songs. At the bottom sits a navigation bar with links to Listen, Explore, and Library."
				/>
			</div>
			<h3 class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold">Moonsound</h3>
			<p class="!mb-12">
				Moonsound is a concept for a music player I originally had back
				in 2015 around the LollyDrop days, now reimagined for an
				entirely different design landscape. I'm a big fan of glass and
				blur effects in design, so I took this as an opportunity to
				experiment with those.
			</p>
			<div
				class="aspect-[9/14] max-h-[90vh] w-full max-sm:aspect-[9/18] max-sm:px-4"
			>
				<iframe
					class="h-full w-full rounded-3xl border-2 border-dotted border-white/20"
					src="https://www.figma.com/embed?embed_host=share&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.figma.com/proto/3hZxdIKmSWdHoEKCBFbbNv/Leisurely-Prototype?page-id=0%3A1&type=design&node-id=4-2239&t=z7W8VCi9l92h8pxM-0&scaling=scale-down&starting-point-node-id=4%3A2239&hide-ui=1"
					allowfullscreen
					loading="lazy"></iframe>
			</div>
			<h3 class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold">Leisurely</h3>
			<p>
				Leisurely is a concept I created in college for a fellow
				student's startup idea: an inspired take on a new clothes
				shopping experience. I was given free rein over the branding and
				UI, so I decided to go with a bold black and white look, putting
				focus on the clothes.
			</p>
			<p class="!mb-12">
				You can view the prototype separately <Link
					href="https://figma.com/proto/3hZxdIKmSWdHoEKCBFbbNv/Leisurely-Prototype?page-id=0%3A1&type=design&node-id=4-2239&t=z7W8VCi9l92h8pxM-0&scaling=scale-down&starting-point-node-id=4%3A2239&hide-ui=1"
					>on Figma.</Link
				>
			</p>
			<div class="card">
				<Image
					src={grid}
					alt="The howdoesgrid.work website, showing a grid layout with 3 rows and 3 columns, with a gap of 1rem between each row and column."
					class="rounded-lg"
				/>
			</div>
			<h3 class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold">
				howdoesgrid.work
			</h3>
			<p>
				howdoesgrid.work is a simple site I created to aid in the
				creation of grid layouts using CSS grid. The website allows you
				to set a name for your grid; define rows, columns, and gaps; and
				even provides a handy visualization in addition to the CSS
				required to create such a layout.
			</p>
			<p class="!mb-12">
				You can visit the site <Link
					href="https://mueller-alex.github.io/howdoesgridwork/"
					>here</Link
				> and the source code on <Link
					href="https://github.com/mueller-alex/howdoesgridwork"
					>GitHub.</Link
				>
			</p>
			<div class="card">
				<Image
					src={sourcery}
					alt="The Sourcery website, showing a grid layout with 3 rows and 3 columns, with a gap of 1rem between each row and column."
					class="aspect-video rounded-lg object-cover object-top"
				/>
			</div>
			<h3 class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold">Sourcery</h3>
			<p>
				While working for Greenhouse Studios during college, the main
				project I worked on was Sourcery. Sourcery is a webapp that
				grants access to archival documents from anywhere in the world.
				After selecting choosing one of several supported repositories,
				a researcher can submit a document request to a "Sourcer," who
				will attempt to retrieve the document(s) and upload them to
				Sourcery, where the researcher can then view and download them.
			</p>
			<p>
				As a UX Engineer on this project, I handled both design and
				front-end development. This was my first experience using Vue,
				but as I mentioned prior, I was able to pick it up quickly and
				start contributing actual, deployable code within a week.
			</p>
			<p class="!mb-12">
				You can view my more in-depth exploration into my work for
				Sourcery on my <Link href="https://muellr.xyz/projects/sourcery"
					>portfolio,</Link
				> and you can learn more about Sourcery on <Link
					href="https://sourceryapp.org">its website.</Link
				>
			</p>
			<div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
				<ImageTile
					src={lollydrop}
					alt="Colorful drop-shaped icon with concentric layers in white, red, yellow, and blue, representing the LollyDrop app."
					caption="LollyDrop"
				/>
				<ImageTile
					src={tasker}
					alt="Gear-shaped icon with a yellow lightning bolt through the center, symbolizing the Tasker task management app."
					caption="Tasker"
				/>
				<ImageTile
					src={contacts}
					alt="Icon depicting a contact card, the left two thirds blue with a white user glyph inside, and the last third grey with 3 grey lines representing contact information."
					caption="Contacts"
				/>
				<ImageTile
					src={chrome}
					alt="Circular icon with red, yellow, and green segments around a blue center, evoking the Chrome browser logo with Material Design styling."
					caption="Chrome"
				/>
			</div>
			<h3 class="font-extended text-2xl font-semibold">LollyDrop</h3>
			<p>
				As an Android nerd, the launch of Google's Material Design in
				2014 was really what got me hooked on design. I loved (and still
				love) the focus on depth and smooth motion. I especially loved
				the look of the new app icons, enough so that I learned how to
				make my own.
			</p>
			<p>
				In 2015, I released LollyDrop, a free Android icon pack giving
				apps new and old the Material Design treatment. It eventually
				reached just over 71,000 downloads on the Google Play Store,
				which is more than I ever could have imagined.
			</p>

			<!-- <p>
				CSS in particular feels like a puzzle to be solved. Sometimes
				you have the box to look at, sometimes that final image is just
				sitting in your brain somewhere.
			</p>
			<p>
				In practice, I tend to do a bit of both. I jump straight into
				high fidelity mockups â€” Figma makes it too easy â€” conjuring up a
				basic layout and some components, then turning to code to truly
				iterate on the design. I commonly find that actually
				implementing the design can expose flaws that I wouldn't have
				seen otherwise, and new ideas I wouldn't have thought of
				otherwise.
			</p>

			<p>I love puzzles, and I love helping people</p> -->
		</div>
		<div
			id="tailwind"
			class="relative col-span-2 mb-12 flex w-full flex-col justify-between gap-4"
		>
			<SectionTitle
				href="#tailwind"
				title="Alex + Tailwind"
				icon="mdi:tailwind"
				colors="bg-sky-500 text-white border-sky-400"
			/>
			<p>
				Thank you for taking the time to read through this, and I hope
				you liked what you saw! This sounds like a dream job for me, so
				I'm incredibly happy for the opportunity to apply. I've been a
				big fan and proponent of Tailwind since I started using it, and
				the idea of getting able to actually contribute to it sounds
				amazing.
			</p>
			<p>
				I am definitely earlier in my career than other applicants will
				be, but I think that's not a bad thing. I'm eager to learn and
				grow, and don't come with a lot of preconceived notions about
				how things should be done.
			</p>
			<p>
				I love the flexibilty and velocity that a small team holds. My
				experience with Greenhouse Studios was with around 15 people
				total, and I loved the amount of freedom that came with that.
				Having trustworthy and skilled coworkers made it easy for things
				to get done, as there didn't have to be a massive ticketing
				system with strict workflows that only some people can create,
				yada, yada, yada.
			</p>
			<p>
				I'd love to hear from you, whether it's to talk more about this
				opportunity, or simply if you had any feedback on how I could
				improve!
			</p>
			<p>
				Below I have my portfolio linked along with some of my social
				profiles. Once again, thank you for the opportunity, and I hope
				to hear from you soon!
			</p>
			<a
				class="group relative mx-auto flex w-fit flex-1 items-center justify-between rounded-full border-4 border-dotted border-sky-500 bg-sky-400 p-2 text-4xl text-white transition-all duration-500 ease-spring-1 active:translate-y-1 active:scale-100 hocus:rotate-[1turn] hocus:scale-110 dark:border-sky-200"
